A New Demo by Cream..

There was a crew in a distant land who once decided to 'Do Things' with 
their computers.. Some of those things were distinctly musical, as such 
previous efforts as 'Steps' (no, nothing to do with the annoying Abba 
clone group of that name who seem to get a top ten placing every five 
minutes!) 'Things that make you go Hmmm', and of course, the somewhat 
legendary 'CreamSID' player..

Their latest demo, quite a long time in the making, confirms the 
reputation of Cream, and their excellent soundchip musician, Tao, as an 
extremely talented bunch of people..

You might argue that it is 'only' an ST demo, you may suggest that it 
is only really based around variations on a single effect, and ask why 
has it taken them two years to finish it.. I would say that this demo 
is one of the best put together and well designed demos anywhere!

It is an ST demo, but can run on almost anything Atari related, even 
the Pacifist emulator on the PC.. A technical 'first' for this demo, is 
that the majority of it was coded on Pacifist, rather than a raw ST or 
Falcon! (Also a large part of the graphics were prepared with Photoshop 
to save time, an excellent use of the available tools to hand..)

It can run as a classic autobooting floppy disk, it is presented to us 
as an MSA file, but there is a considerately provided TOS executable 
for those of us with hard drives and reasonable (2 MB and above) RAM 
sizes..

I run the demo.. First, an option screen to run the demo, or copy to 
disk, with a background tune, then having decided to get into the 
action, a brief option menu makes sure the Falcon internal speaker 
stays firmly 'off'! The first sign of the demo proper is a brilliant 
sixteen colour loading picture by Agent T, leaving us in 'confusion'!  

The first of many of Tao's wonderful tunes starts up at this point, a 
YM tune, with distinctive SID-like overtones.. A bunch of self-
confident credits stab their way onto the screen, the prequel for the 
first main part of the demo..

This is the 'effect' part of the demo, a wonderful liquid-like swirling 
tunnel plasma, with an almost 3-D feel in some places! Hard to 
describe, wonderful to see in action, and very well interpreted for an 
ST's limited range of colours onscreen.. This is a single effect, but 
with many variations on the theme, all of them wonderful.. More 
credits, and a great number of greetings push to the front of the 
screen to make themselves seen as well..

Just when this part of the demo starts to 'rap', you get the feeling it 
is time to move onto the second part, and give the spacebar a prod.. We 
gratifyingly get another Agent T stunner of a loading screen, with 
another brilliant hand-drawn sixteen colour picture to while away the 
wait for the mid-section of the demo to load..

This is, predictably perhaps, a music selector screen, with around a 
dozen or so Tao tunes awaiting your ears.. This screen as a slightly 
'Cyberpunk' feel in its design.. The first surprise is that these Tao 
Tunes are all SIDchip based! Well maybe not so much of a surprise, if 
you think of it as a logical progression, Cream produce a SIDchip 
player, next step, a SIDchip composer! (So when are the rest of us 
going to get to have a play with this one!? I fancy a shot at being the 
'third worst' SIDchip musician on the Atari scene!)

Banging on the spacebar produces the next item of goodness, an Agent T 
produced slideshow, this seemingly done in some kind of watercolour 
effect (converted from a painting?) and looking confident, self-
assured, and totally brilliant.. A little bit a story along the lines 
of "Loss" in there as well..

Having watched the slideshow, and enjoyed the tunes, you might well 
think that this is all, but there is one final surprise.. Yes, the 
reset demo, first seen in 'Things that make you go Hmmm' makes a return 
visit to this demo as well.. Having perfected a reset routine that 
works on all machines, there was never any sense in Cream keeping it 
for only one demo.. This final part consists of a return to the swirly 
plasma with credits seen earlier, but with more abstract objects 
blended in, such as a Peace symbol, and most stunning of all, a pair of 
eyes, in a 3-D fashion.. Again, the effect needs to be seen to be 
really believed, but it is artistic and understated..

I enjoyed watching Cream 'Do Things', and I'm sure you will too!

Ratings..

Graphix:- 94% - Oh yes, brilliant individual work, and superb overall 
standard of presentation.. This demo reaches new heights of maturity of 
design.. Did I mention this was an ST demo?

Sonix:- 92% - No arguments here either, Some of the very best soundchip 
music for all you soundchip purists and SID fans out there..

Gee-Whiz:- 97% - Let me see now, coded on Pacifist, designed to run 
easily on Pacifist, liquid swirly tunnel plasma thing that I've never 
seen before, original SID tunes by Atari composer, Agent T doing ST 
graphics really well, and a reset demo that damn well works on 
everything too!

Overall:- 95% - One of these things worth doing!

 CiH - Feb 1st '99

