Cream ... do things

Experienced by Richard Davey (rich@atari.org)

Agent T, TAO and Candyman claim that this demo is just intended to be a 
sign of life from Cream. If that's the case, they look very alive 
indeed and their vital signs are strong!

At its heart this demo is essentially one really nice effect, a 
slideshow and an awesome selection of SID-chip music from TAO. But it's 
put together with a certain style and design that enhances its content 
rather than undermine it. The opening effect is really rather 
beautiful, being a combination of plasma tunnels and liquid effects. 
All blend together seemlessly, colour palettes perfectly chosen so as 
to make everything look as smooth as possible; and it works. A quick 
tap of the space bar takes you to an Agent T picture and finally into 
the music selector.

>From here you get to pick from 12 TAO tunes. All of them using his 
newly developed SID routines and all of them really beating the hell 
out of the YM. Music ranges from the slow and trancey "Lost" to an 
almost Japanese offering from "Intensity" and some deep and moving bass 
sounds for "One on One".

The tunes have an almost "digi" feel about them, as if they could be 
soundtracker modules in part. But you know inside it's just a homage to 
TAO's true skill with chip music. There is little point me "reviewing" 
each track as everyone will have their own personal favourite (mine 
being Nostalgia). But rest assured there is some great ear-candy here.

If you press space again while in the music screen, you are taken into 
an Agent T slideshow "somewhere in another world". The pictures all 
lead on from one another to form a story, the style is hand drawn 
almost like a comic book. The story unfolds as a boy finds a strange 
glowing ball in an alley and it progresses to a rather predictable but 
entertaining climax.

In the background TAO struts his stuff of course. There is one last 
treat in store if you hit the reset switch. Some more of Candymans 
great colour swirling effects and a booming TAO tune.

However what is most interesting about this demo are the moral issues 
behind its development. Agent T openly admits to having drawn and 
rendered all the graphics in Photoshop, while Candyman coded the 
majority of the demo using PaCifiST. This in itself has caused various 
discussions on IRC channels, is an ST demo really an ST demo if most of 
it was developed on a PC? It's an interesting question indeed but not 
one which is particularly new to the Atari platform. During its prime 
plenty of the games that came out for the ST had their graphics, code 
and to some extent music ported from the Amiga versions. Those lovely 
raytraced Psygnosis intros for example - some of them crafted on the 
Amiga, others on the PC as time went on.

There is a classic thread throughout the whole of computing showing how 
one machine aided in the development of productions for another, even 
if the end result wasn't even useable on it. It seems that this trend 
has now migrated onto ST demos. I don't hold anything against Agent T 
using Photoshop to get his work done because at the end of the day, 
it's only a tool - just like Degas Elite is a tool. The fact that 
Candyman used PaCifiST to code his demo I think is more a testament to 
the skill of Frederic Gidouin in coding PaCifiST than a derogatory blow 
against Candyman. It's also another firm sign to those who said that 
PaCifiST had/has nothing to offer the "real" Atari world.

But what is the real Atari world now? Not many of us own just an Atari 
machine, some do.. but not all. We live in and around PCs and Macs and 
Amigas as well. The results of the tools on those machines are 
migrating to the Atari. It's almost enevitable, but the issue is should 
we really care? Does it matter how those pictures got into Do Things? 
They still had to be created somewhere, they had to be drawn on a 
computer somewhere. The talent behind them is still the same, 
regardless of their point of origin. And I say it is this that we 
should celebrate.

